    "created_at": "2016-08-10T09:43:36Z",
    "updated_at": "2016-08-10T09:43:36Z",
    "body": "I don't know if the changes would be useful outside of Electron, AFAIK Chrome/Chromium only uses the app indicator in a \"Unity compatible\" way. But I agree, the changes are pretty big, so trying to push them straight into the Chromium project might make more sense than making a huge patch file.\n\nThe problem I have with this is that this greatly increases the scope and impact of the changes, and I have no experience with the whole testing / [try server stuff](https://www.chromium.org/developers/testing/try-server-usage) (and I don't even know if I can use it). Currently, I just build using libchromiumcontent's build system and test manually, and even that is pushing the limits of my workstation (especially since I do it in a VM). I'm reading up on the Chromium project docs, but any pointers on how this can be done more smoothly are welcome.\n\nPS. I don't really think this issue is a bug, IMO the `enhancement` label fits better. Also, since it only impacts distributions using app indicator (i.e Ubuntu Unity), `linux-distribution-specific` looks like a more specific label than `linux` (IMO it should even be called `distribution-specific`. There's nothing stopping you from running Gnome or Unity on top of e.g BSD). I'm planning to make a different issue for the GTK status icon.\n"
  },
